'Cangjie programming language_exception_exception_overview': 'In Cangjie code language, Exceptions in Cangjie are special errors that can be caught and handled by programmers. They represent abnormal behavior during program execution, such as array out-of-bounds, division by zero, overflow, or illegal input. To ensure system correctness and robustness, many software systems include extensive error detection and handling code.
Exceptions are not part of the normal program functionality. Once an exception occurs, the program must immediately handle it by transferring control from normal execution to the exception handling part. Cangjie provides an exception handling mechanism to deal with various runtime exceptions.
In Cangjie, exceptions are divided into two main categories:
Error: Represents internal system errors and resource exhaustion errors during runtime. Applications should not throw this type of error. If an internal error occurs, it should be reported to the user and the program should terminate safely.
Exception: Represents logical errors during runtime or IO errors, such as array out-of-bounds or attempting to open a non-existent file. These exceptions need to be caught and handled in the program.
DEVELOPERS CANNOT inherit from the built-in Error or its subclasses to define custom exceptions, but they can inherit from the built-in Exception or its subclasses.'

Code_Example:
open class FatherException <: Exception {
    public init() {
        super("This is FatherException.")
    }
    public init(message: String) {
        super(message)
    }
    public open override func getClassName(): String {
        "FatherException"
    }
}

class ChildException <: FatherException {
    public init() {
        super("This is ChildException.")
    }
    public open override func getClassName(): String {
        "ChildException"
    }
}
